This year was a bit different - dozens of students opted for virtual learning every day. They will remain at home and do their learning that way while other students will rotate between in-school and virtual learning.

Whichever path a family chose, it all came together today!

Many thanks to the nearly dozen parents who sent us pictures of their child's first day back at school.

post_text:
Attention all 7th-grade parents:

If your child is in grades 7-12 you have access to your child's permanent record information. Since this is your child's first year with this capability we need you to fill out a school tools parent portal request form. This will give you access to your child's grades, schedule, most recently provided contact information, attendance, and discipline information.

If your child is participating in the hybrid schedules they will be bringing home a parent portal request form. This form can be filled out and returned to school by your child on their next scheduled in-person school day.
If your child is remote only you can access the form using the link below, print the form, and email it to rebecca.mcadams@oesj.org . If you would like us to provide you with a hard copy one can be picked up or mailed to you.

Parent Portal Form Link :
https://www.oesj.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Portal_Parent_Consent_Form.pdf

PARENTS OF IN-SCHOOL AND VIRTUAL STUDENTS: As the new school year kicks off, we’d like to share those precious pictures of your students!

Every year, the school district takes dozens of pictures at the OESJ schools on opening day. This year, we’d like to see what you see in the morning – whether it's on your front porch, at your child's at-home work station or heading to the school.

Please snap some back-to-school pictures and send them to us. You can send your pictures to Robert Hanlon at rhanlon@sgcsd.net. We will accept pictures until Wednesday, Sept. 16. PLEASE BE SURE TO LET US KNOW YOUR STUDENT'S GRADE AND SCHOOL.

We will compile all of our community’s photos into a photo album on Facebook and feature some of them on the school district’s website. We look forward to welcoming your children back to school and we wish everyone a wonderful start to the year!

post_text:
Two new benches are in place near the Marge Curtis Auditorium in memory of Ms. Dale Boudry. Ms. Boudry passed away in a bicycle accident on July 1, 2016. She was a special education teacher at OESJ Central School for many years. She was a dedicated educator and friend to many co-workers. Mr. Crowe and Mrs. VanSchaick-Bianci's class began the collection that made the benches possible. A special thank you to all staff members that donated.

A Dale Boudry memorial scholarship is awarded to a graduating senior each year. Donations to the scholarship may be made to the OESJ business office.

2020 Fall Sports Sign Up!

All students have been emailed a Google form to sign up for fall sports for the 2020-2021 school year.

If you going to be in 7th grade in the fall however, you were not emailed the form as your emails are not set up yet. Once your email is set up through the school, the form will be sent to you also via email.

Board member Sarah Barnes was re-elected with 654 votes and Jeremy Brundage was re-elected with 635 votes.

Monday, May 18th between 8 am and 1 pm: Last name M-Z

post_text:
Please remember that OESJ is offering meals for students during this school shutdown.

These meals will be available at both the Jr./Sr. High School and the Elementary School between the hours of 11:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. and they can be picked up by the student, a parent, or family member.

The meals will be picked up in the cafeteria in both buildings, using the rear entrance by the girl’s locker room and cafeteria at the Jr./Sr. High School and the front main entrance at the Elementary School. The breakfast will include an entrée (bagel, muffin, cereal), fruit and a juice and the lunch will include an entrée (sandwich), fruit, carrots, and milk.

If you are not able to pick up the lunches at the school, please contact your building principal so arrangements can be made.

post_text:
Five students from Mrs. Kelly's 9th grade Honors English class attended the annual "Pen in Hand" Writer's Conference this past weekend. The conference, held in Little Falls and organized by a local group of educators and writers, connects high school students with those in the writing industry. During the two-day event students met with local writers who discussed best practices, publishing, and editing. All five students who attended stated they would want to go again in future years citing meeting other young writers as one of the best parts of the weekend.

Pictured here, from left to right, are Jaslynn Leach, Jade Dygert, Christian Mosher, Emileigh Moore, and Hannah Christensen.

post_text:
Mrs. Heroth's first grade attended a virtual field trip to Dutch Hollow Farm in Schodack Landing, NY on November 12, 2019. The students enjoyed learning about what the cows eat, how they milk the cows and where the milk goes. They also got to visit calves in the nursery barn with farmer Nate and listen to how he takes care of them. This was a great opportunity made available by the New York Dairy Association.

The class was very excited last week to receive a package from Cabot that included cheese snacks, patches, stickers, and even a blow-up cow!

There are several dates that you should keep in mind:

Wednesday, Jan. 22 – Personal registration (if not already registered) from 2 PM to 6 PM at the elementary school, 6486 State Highway 29 St. Johnsville, NY 13452
Jan. 28 – Applications for absentee ballots that are to be mailed must be received by today.
Feb. 3 – Absentee ballots must be picked up by today
Feb. 4 – Absentee ballots must be received by 5PM today
Feb. 4 – Voting held from 12 to 8 p.m. today at both schools, depending on where you live.

shared_text:
OESJ Athletic Department
January 9 at 4:24 PM ·

OESJ Von Baker commits to Cornell for baseball

OESJ RHP Von Baker has committed to Head Coach Dan Pepicelli and the Cornell University. Cornell participates in NCAA Division I as part of the Ivy League.

Baker becomes the first player ever from OESJ High School to commit to a Division I school.

“Von is a true student athlete,” said OESJ Athletic Coordinator Travis Heiser. “He works hard inside and outside of the classroom. With a 92 MPH fastball, standing at 6’7” and weighing in at 235, he is a big presence on the pitcher’s mound. Also, he excels in the classroom.”

“He’s a very smart kid and academics are important to him and his family,” Heiser said. “He had a goal to play baseball at the Division 1 level while attending a top level college, and everyone at OESJ is happy he gets the opportunity to do it.”

We would like to congratulate Von and the Baker family on his commitment to Cornell.

post_text: The students in Mrs. VanHooker’s class recently collaborated with Mrs. Kelly’s senior English class to do a research project about how Christmas is celebrated in other countries. One of the requirements was to make a food unique to that country that might be eaten at Christmas time. Mrs. VanHooker’s class learned to make homemade pasta and meat sauce to share with the entire group. The recipe was one brought back from the Tuscany region in Italy by Mrs. Conte. The students helped dice onions, fry meat and cook the sauce one day and the second day they made the dough for the pasta. Rolling and cutting the dough was a different experience for the students. Everyone had a great time doing this. They were extremely excited to be able to enjoy the food they had prepared. It was delicious!!

On Tuesday December 3, 2019 OESJ held its annual Spelling Bee at the JR/SR High School Auditorium. 30 students from grade 4 to grade 8 qualified to compete in this local Spelling Bee by winning their classroom bees. The Bee went 13 rounds before EmmaJo Schmidtmann was crowned as the champion. EmmaJo will represent OESJ at the Regional Spelling Bee at Proctor’s Theater in Schenectady, NY on February 4. Good luck, EmmaJo!

Picture 1- Kaylee Heroth (2nd place), EmmaJo Schmidtmann (champion), Myles Hayes (4th place), Peyton Spicci (3rd place)

Students previewed each other's book's before they were read aloud by their authors. The readings were followed by a snack and students complimenting each other on their excellent writing.

post_text:
Amethyst Scherer, the daughter of Shayla Dixon, was recently selected for the Area All-State Mixed Chorus for Zone 7. Amethyst has been working towards this goal since 9th grade, attending NYSSMA (New York School of Music Association) Solo Festivals each year. To earn a place in this elite chorus, a student needs to achieve a high score on a level 6 NYSSMA solo and be chosen by the NYSSMA committee. Several hundred students apply for this choir, and only an elite few are chosen. Amethyst is the first chorus student chosen in the new OESJ district.

In addition, Amethyst just received notice that she was chosen as part of an elite choral group at Roberts Wesleyan College called the Honors Choir 2020. Congratulations Amethyst on your hard work, dedication, and commitment to your vocal career.

post_text: Dialing 2-1-1 can help parents and guardians quickly, easily and anonymously connect to resources within their communities. 2-1-1 is a nationwide toll-free dial-in service and website to help people in non-emergency situations access local public health and safety resources, including getting help with food, shelter or non-emergency mental health care; tax assistance and veterans’ services; support for someone at risk for suicide or domestic violence; and more. There are no income or residency requirements to access this helpline. For more information about the services available through 2-1-1, visit 211.org.

Visitors to the school buildings should bring their drivers licenses since OESJ is now using the Raptor Visitor Management System. You will need to show your license or other government identification in order to get into the buildings.

The system compares visitors government-issued identification against a comprehensive national list of registered sex offenders.

The Raptor system is used at more than 20,000 K-12 campuses across the country.

November 3, 2019 at 2:33 PM ·

OESJ sixth graders climbed Kane Mountain in Caroga Lake as part of their Adirondack Studies on October 18th. Students used field guides and i-pads to identify native Adirondack Species after learning the history of the park in science class. They brought along their science journals to write down observations at the summit and participated in a “Nature Scavenger Hunt.”

Students also had the chance to climb the Kane Mountain Fire Tower and enjoy the spectacular views. Heidi Sprouse, OESJ Pre-K teacher and author spoke with the students before their trip. She talked about her book, “Adirondack Sundown” the first in her “Lost in the Adirondacks” series, which takes place in the wilderness surrounding Kane Mountain. Sixth graders’ names were put in a drawing and one boy and one girl each won a copy of the book!

post_text:
OESJ’s seven Board of Education members spent countless hours freely donating their time to ensure that every child receives an excellent education!

The New York State School Boards Association recognizes October 21 – 25 as School Board Recognition Week.

This is a time to promote awareness and understanding of the important work performed by school board members. Oppenheim-Ephratah-St. Johnsville is joining all public school districts across the state to celebrate School Board Recognition Week to honor local board members for their commitment to OESJ and its children.

“It takes strong schools to build a strong community, and these men and women devote countless hours to making sure our schools are helping every child learn at a higher level,” Interim Superintendent Joseph Natale said. “They make the tough decisions every month and spend many hours studying education issues and regulations in order to provide the kind of accountability our citizens expect.”

Read more here - https://www.oesj.org/many-thanks-to-oesj-board-of-education-members-for-school-board-recognition-week/

OESJ Athletic Department
October 8, 2019 at 6:14 PM ·

The varsity volleyball team will be participating in the Side-Out Foundation's Power of Pink Breast Cancer Awareness tournament on 10/19 and we need your help fundraising for this great cause.

The funds raised for Side-Out go toward a clinical trial specifically for patients with stage 4 breast cancer, the most advanced form of the disease and the least funded area of research.

Here is the link for the fundraiser

https://giving.side-out.org/campaigns/16274#/

Thank you so much for helping,

Coach Schmidt and the OESJ Lady Wolves Varsity Volleyball Team

shared_text:
OESJ Athletic Department
October 7, 2019 at 7:58 PM ·

Josie Brundage is set to play in the Inaugural Section 2 girls golf Championship. She is the first golfer from OESJ to compete in sectionals.

Good luck Josie!!

The Northeastern New York Section of the PGA will offer assistance with golf tournament services to Section 2 and more specifically to the Section 2 Girls Golf Committee at Fairways of Halfmoon Golf Course to help conduct the Inaugural Girls Golf Sectional & State Qualifier.

Dottie Pepper who is a Section 2 standout athlete and tremendous advocate of junior golf, is excited to attend the student-athlete luncheon and awards ceremony following play and celebrate the achievements of the girls along with the coaches, school administrators, NENY PGA Professionals, and all those who provided support for the high school girls golf movement.
